Got it — if you’re using Docker, then Docker is filling up / because Docker’s default data directory is:

/var/lib/docker (on /, which is 100% full in your screenshot)

Even if /mnt/data on /dev/sdb has tons of space, Docker won’t use it unless you move Docker’s data-root there.

Here’s the clean, safe way.

0) Confirm Docker data directory and size
docker info 2>/dev/null | egrep -i 'Docker Root Dir|Storage Driver'
sudo du -sh /var/lib/docker 2>/dev/null
df -h /
df -h /mnt/data

1) Stop Docker
sudo systemctl stop docker
sudo systemctl stop docker.socket 2>/dev/null || true


Check it’s stopped:

sudo systemctl is-active docker || true

2) Copy Docker data to /mnt/data
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/data/docker
sudo rsync -aHAX --numeric-ids /var/lib/docker/ /mnt/data/docker/

3) Tell Docker to use /mnt/data/docker as its root

Create/update /etc/docker/daemon.json:

sudo mkdir -p /etc/docker
cat <<'EOF' | sudo tee /etc/docker/daemon.json
{
  "data-root": "/mnt/data/docker"
}
EOF

4) Move old directory out of the way (don’t delete yet)
sudo mv /var/lib/docker /var/lib/docker.bak
sudo mkdir -p /var/lib/docker

5) Start Docker and verify
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl status docker --no-pager


Verify Docker is now using the new path:

docker info | grep -i "Docker Root Dir"


You should see:

Docker Root Dir: /mnt/data/docker
